pq:text.pq:tspan: Hi, Abbey, how is your program going?
Great, but it would be even better if some of these images could move!
Kate is away. Let's ask Phil
Hi, guys! What can I do for you?
We want to get things moving in our program.
Ok. Well let's start with some game terminology.
An image that moves in a game is called a sprite

Did you know that the termspriteis a broad term referring to a number ofSupernaturallegendary creatures. The term is generally used in reference toelf-like creatures, includingfairies,dwarves and the likes of it, but can also signify variousspiritual beings includingghosts.
DID YOU KNOW?
in SwinGame a Sprite is an image with a location in the game, and some other properties.
How can we create a sprite for our bug image?
Well firstly you need to declare a "variable".
A variable is a part of your program that is used to store a value.
We can use a variable to refer to our spite. Anything we do to the variable will manipulate the sprite.
Ok We'll give it to go!
Well, in SwinGame each sprite has a "Movement" property
Phil, our sprite isn't moving!
This defines how each sprite moves each time it's updated.
Try setting the X movement of your sprite to 0.5
Remember to update the sprite
We can do that
Argh It falls off the edge of the screen!
Remember, the computer is unintelligent; it does exactly what you tell it.
What you can do is use an if statement to keep the sprite on the screen. If the sprite has reached the edge of the screen, change its movement to -0.5.
This will make it move to the left.
How can we check if it has gone off the screen?
The sprite has a position, size, and movement.The sprite has an X and Y value for its position
and a width and height for its size.
Its movement is accessed as Movement.X and Movement.Y.
To check it against the screen, we need to check its right edge against the screen width.
Ok I can give it a try
Yeah! We can do it!
Doh now it goes off the left side of the screen.
We can apply the same logic, but now with the left edge of the sprite, and the left of the screen.
That's it.. See how you go
you could also move up and down using Movement.Y, and the height of the sprite ans the screen.
